content.description: Update:  This climb is actually on the west side of Financial Wall and not up on Key's Point.  The crux is at the start. What's good the finger crack after the traverse. What's bad a little rotten at the start.
content.location: This is technically on the west side of Financial Wall.

climbs.name: High Interest
climbs.fa: Herb Laeger and Bob Yoho, Feb. 1986

content.description:
High Interest starts at the right side of a level section at the base of the center wall.  It takes a hand crack with a pod up to a traverse right into another hand crack.

This is a stout climb with a continuous nature.  Moves start right off the deck with an awkward series to gain the base of a pod.  Here the left lean and wide crack makes this perhaps the crux of the route.  A rest can be eked after this in the flare at the base of the hand traverse.  The traverse is an airy set of moves, without much help from the feet.  From here deep hand jamming with an even more pronounced left lean finish the route.

Easy descent climber's right.
content.protection: Full Standard Rack plus a #3.5 or a #4 Camalot.

content.description: Just right of Higer Yield this route passes a bush about 35' up.  Gritty and a bit awkward, this route is the only easy route on the wall.  Passing the bush higher up also proves to be annoying.  Worth doing if in the area, but not worth extra effort.

This route is located on a sub wall lower and right of the main Financial wall.  It start at base of a set of thin cracks which lead to a stance below a bulge.

The start is a series of finger jams and pulls which feel more like face climbing than crack.  An off balance move leads to the stance below the bulge. A powerfull series of moves through the bulge lead to a short hand crack.  Finish right and up to the top.

Perhaps 2 of 5 stars.
